post_text:
Bee Bee Nation,

Today's episode presents two challenges for our students to participate in by connecting to home and to Critical Essential Workers in the field that your family may know.

Challenge #1--Watcha' Up 2?

--Share a picture that describes what activities your student has used to fill their free time at home.

Challenge #2--Critical Essential Workers

This challenge will concentrate on the Healthcare/Public Health Sector and Information Technology Sector.

Do we know someone working in or with the healthcare/medical field in some capacity?

Do we know someone working within the technology, computer, internet or cellular providers? News, radio, reporters, technicians? etc. etc.

Please assist your student in these challenges, we are hoping to receive pictures and descriptions of people you may know helping our area "keep on, keepin' on".



Challenge pictures/descriptions can be sent to any of these 3 email addresses:

shoufler@wcusd15.org

damery@wcusd15.org

compardo@wcusd15.org

post_text:
Kicking off the Great Kindness Challenge at WJHS today! Students are asked to complete 50 random acts of kindness in and out of school this week. #bulletpride

This morning WJHS students were invited to participate in "The Great Kindness Challenge" a positive, proactive kindness initiative, reaching millions of students and families every year. Nearly 15 million students in 27,656 schools in 115 countries are dedicated to creating a
culture of kindness and compassion on campuses worldwide.

All students will receive The Great Kindness Challenge checklist, which has 50 acts of kindness listed.
Please encourage your child to complete as many acts of kindnessn as possible.

We are also happy to invite YOU to participate using the Family Edition checklist. Your family can complete the checklist anytime and anywhere. Find the checklist at: www.greatkindnesschallenge.org

Together, let’s show the world that KINDNESS MATTERS; January 27-31 is the happiest week of the year

post_text:
Congratulations to our Cross Country team and individual runners at State this weekend. Our girls team finished 16th out of 27 teams overall at the Class 2A level!

Riley Mendenhall (8th grade) finished individually 19th overall! This is only the 2nd time a female WJHS runner has finished in the top 25, achieving "All-State" ranking! Way to go Riley!

Drew Mirable represented the boy's team as an individual runner and finished 101st out of 237 runners! Great job Drew!

All of the runners pictured contributed to the success of our state runners. Countless miles pushing each other to be their best paid off once again. Great job runners and Coach Surbeck!

post_text:
Mrs Heaps and her Geometric Design class have been inventing and creating. Here is an example of a Rube Goldberg Machine students created.

A Rube Goldberg machine is a machine intentionally designed to perform a simple task in an indirect and overcomplicated fashion. Often, these machines consist of a series of simple devices that are linked together to produce a domino effect, in which each device triggers the next one, and the original goal is achieved only after many steps.

The Williamsville High School Music Programs are proud to present the Williamsville High School Spring Fine Arts Festival for the first time outside at the Sherman Municipal Park. This event is sponsored by Williamsville High School and the Village of Sherman.

The WHS student art show will be displayed throughout the evening beginning at 5:30 in the large gazebo. Music will begin in the amphitheater at 6:00 PM featuring the WHS Combined Choir, Concert Band, Vocal Jazz Ensemble, and Jazz Band. Be sure to bring a blanket or folding chair for seating!

Barbecue dinners, snacks, and drinks will be provided by the combined Williamsville Band Boosters and Vocal Music Boosters.
There is no charge for admission and all are welcome! All concession proceeds will go to help WCUSD15 music programs.
